s about air and the earth’s atmosphere in natural philosophy, as well as to the era’s theories of the supernatural and fascination with social manners—or, as they are now known, “airs.” Lewis thus offers a striking new interpretation of several standard features of the Enlightenment—the scientific revolution, the decline of magic, character-based sociability, and the rise of the novel—that considers them in terms of the romance of air that permeates and connects them. As it explores key episodes in the history of natural philosophy and in major literary works like Paradise Lost, “The Rape of the Lock,” Robinson Crusoe, and The Mysteries of Udolpho, this book promises to change the atmosphere of eighteenth-century studies and the history of the novel.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aEnglish fictiony17th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aEnglish fictiony18th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aWeather in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  aliterary, atmosphere, british, britain, fiction, 1600s, 1700s, 18th century, literature, english major, college, academic, scholarly, university, novelist, immaterial, material world, natural philosophy, enlightenment, era, time period, supernatural, manners, social studies, community, relationships, interpersonal, communication, romance, philosophical, society, polite, rape of the lock, alexander pope, tom jones, canon.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831106353860 cprintz978022647669840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226476711423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226476711/original  a978-3-11-063538-6  University of Chicago Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles